    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "d47f255c1711dc8b0c29b2b5a8f1773a3394e7c9",
    "explanation": "AWS Lambda runs event-triggered functions with no instance, OS or capacity to manage, which is the definition of serverless / Function as a Service. PaaS is the classic trap: it is close because the provider also manages the platform, but in PaaS you still deploy and keep a running application (and pay for its idle time), while Lambda bills only per invocation."
  },
  {
    "id": "sample2-q004",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "cloud-computing",
    "subtopic": "edge-computing",
    "stem": "Edge computing reduces:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Security",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Bandwidth",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Latency",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Storage",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "Sample -2.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "practice",
      "originalNumber": 4
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "6a06dd6e19f9b88288a0edfc619a1814f9e27294",
    "explanation": "Edge computing processes data at or near the source instead of shipping it to a distant data centre, which cuts the round-trip time and therefore the latency. Bandwidth is the standard trap: edge does reduce bandwidth usage as a side effect, but latency reduction is the defining benefit and the keyed answer."
  },
  {
    "id": "sample2-q005",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "cloud-computing",
    "subtopic": "elasticity",
    "stem": "Which cloud feature automatically adjusts resources?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Virtualization",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Elasticity",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Encryption",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Metering",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "Sample -2.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "practice",
      "originalNumber": 5
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "666d419b206d08af11ba04e13682d17db05550c3",
    "explanation": "Elasticity is the cloud property of automatically scaling resources up when demand rises and back down when it falls, with no manual provisioning. The distractors are all real cloud features but none of them adjust capacity: virtualization is the underlying abstraction of hardware, encryption protects data, and metering only measures usage so it can be billed."
  },
  {
    "id": "sample2-q006",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "network-fundamentals",
    "stem": "What is a computer network?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "A collection of standalone computers.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "A collection of interconnected devices that share resources and information.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "A single powerful computer that manages all data.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "A system for storing data on external hard drives.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "Sample -2.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "practice",
      "originalNumber": 6
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "93980658282265160849141bc08c559854a6d567",
    "explanation": "A computer network is a set of interconnected devices (nodes) linked by transmission media so they can share resources and exchange information. Option A is the exact negation: 'standalone' computers are by definition not networked."
  },
  {
